			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~cascadingstylesheet">cascadingstylesheet</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~cascadingstylesheet">( 140919 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64587389">		
		on Saturday June 29, 2024 @07:50AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23371653&amp;cid=64587389">#64587389</a>)
		<small><a href="//slashdot.org/~cascadingstylesheet/journal/" title="Tuesday May 04, 2021 @11:02PM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64587389"><p><div class="quote"><p>He said the role of a modern university is to prepare the students for their professional careers, and the reality is they are going to use various AI tools after graduation. So, they'd be better off knowing how to do it properly.</p></div><p>Yep.
</p><p>They <i>are</i> tools. Refusing to use a better tool is stupid. (Yes, yes, worshiping a tool is stupid too, but who's doing that?)
</p><p>Latest cool thing I did with a tool (ChatGPT) -
</p><p>"Given this form {url to the front end of a giant form on the client's old website}, can you generate an import file for {form tool we are going to use} to recreate it on a new website?"
</p><p>"Sure! Here is the import json file for recreating this form in {form tool}<nobr> <wbr></nobr>..."
</p><p>Did I need to tweak a few of the 100+ fields after importing the file?  Sure. But did it save me a few hours?  Yep.
</p><p>A tool. Don't be a Luddite. Learn how to use it.</p></div>
	</div>

